{"title":"Decathlon is bringing a $3999 titanium gravel bike to the U.S. – SOC 2023","link":"https://www.cyclingtips.com/2023/04/decathlon-bikes-titanium-gravel/","date":1682090771000,"content":"<p><span><a href=\"https://cyclingtips.com/tag/decathlon\" target=\"_blank\">Decathlon</a> is far from a household name in North America, but the sporting goods retailer is a true behemoth in Europe. Think of them as the Target version of REI: plenty of in-house brands offering value-packed goods, except Decathalon is targeted at the outdoor industry. Their latest round of bikes displayed at the <a href=\"https://cyclingtips.com/tag/sea-otter-classic\" target=\"_blank\">Sea Otter 2023</a> show off how serious they are about their bikes.</span></p>\n<p><span>We’ll cover Decathalon and their brands – Van Rysel for road and Riverside for gravel – more down the line. In the meantime, here’s a teaser of what they have now and to come. Notables include solid budget carbon road bikes, a titanium gravel bike that somehow costs less than the deposit on a Moots titanium frame, and a high-end tri bike one might see Continental teams use in the near future.</span></p>\n<figure>\n<p></p><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips-Riverside-GRVL-900-Ti-.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips---Riverside-GRVL-900-Ti-\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips-Riverside-GRVL-900-Ti-.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips-Riverside-GRVL-900-Ti-.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>Decathalon’s adventure and gravel subbrand is called Riverside. This one is called the Riverside GRVL 900 Ti, featuring a Fulcrum Rapid Red Gravel wheelset, Shimano GRX one-by drivetrain, and a titanium frameset made by Italian tubing manufacturer Dedacciai. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</figcaption></figure></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips-Riverside-GRVL-900-Ti-logo.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips---Riverside-GRVL-900-Ti-logo\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips-Riverside-GRVL-900-Ti-logo.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips-Riverside-GRVL-900-Ti-logo.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>There are a few things missing from this bike for being a titanium gravel bike. The lack of a top tube bag mount isn’t a big deal, but it is a notable-enough omission. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips-GRVL-900-Ti-drivetrain-1.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips---GRVL-900-Ti-drivetrain\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips-GRVL-900-Ti-drivetrain-1.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips-GRVL-900-Ti-drivetrain-1.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>A Shimano GRX drivetrain is nice to see. The frame is 1x and 2x capable and fits a 700c x 45 mm tire. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</span></figcaption><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-GRVL-900-Ti-seattube.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Decathalon-GRVL-900-Ti-seattube\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-GRVL-900-Ti-seattube.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-GRVL-900-Ti-seattube.jpg?width=190 190w\" /></figure>\n<figure><figcaption><span>The seattube notes the GRVL 900 Ti uses a 3AL-2.5V version of titanium tubing. This isn’t particularly exotic tubing by any means, but based on the tube shapes it should ride pretty well. I would have to see the geometry chart – and ride it on a long-term test – to determine that to be clear. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips-GRVL-900-Ti-welds-1.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips---GRVL-900-Ti-welds\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips-GRVL-900-Ti-welds-1.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips-GRVL-900-Ti-welds-1.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>Some detail on the weld details for the downtube on the GRVL 900 Ti. This is an example of the downtube cable stops. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-Van-Rysel-RCR-Force.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Decathalon-Van-Rysel-RCR-Force\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-Van-Rysel-RCR-Force.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-Van-Rysel-RCR-Force.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>This is the Van Rysel RCR Force. Van Rysel is Decathalon’s road bike sub-brand, and the brand has some serious ambitions, including racing in the pro peloton. Van Rysel claims the RCR Force was co-designed for ONERA, a French Aerospace Lab known for their aerodynamics work. This SRAM Force-equipped bike is said to retail at $6999 US. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</span></figcaption></figure>\n</figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-Van-Rysel-RCR-Force-downtube.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Decathalon-Van-Rysel-RCR-Force-downtube\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-Van-Rysel-RCR-Force-downtube.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-Van-Rysel-RCR-Force-downtube.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>There are two versions of the frame that will be available, including a mid-modulus carbon fiber frame, and a lighter high-modulus carbon frame that Decathalon says pro teams will be riding in the near future. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips-Van-Rysel-RCR-Force-headtube.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips---Van-Rysel-RCR-Force-headtube\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips-Van-Rysel-RCR-Force-headtube.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips-Van-Rysel-RCR-Force-headtube.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>The RCR road bike uses Deda’s ACR internal cable routing option. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)<br />\n</span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips-Van-Rysel-RCR-Force-seattube.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips---Van-Rysel-RCR-Force-seattube\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips-Van-Rysel-RCR-Force-seattube.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-bikes-CyclingTips-Van-Rysel-RCR-Force-seattube.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>They’re proud that the bike was “Designed in Flanders.” And look at that seattube junction! Look at those aerodynamics in action. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-XCR-TT-bike.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Decathalon-XCR-TT-bike\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-XCR-TT-bike.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-XCR-TT-bike.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>There are few details on the Van Rysel XCR TT bike, but it looks like some serious work was put into their time trial bike. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-XCR-TT-dropouts.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Decathalon-XCR-TT-dropouts\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-XCR-TT-dropouts.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-XCR-TT-dropouts.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>The coordinates here go to Kipstadium, an indoor gym and sports center owned by Decathlon just outside Roubaix. The dropouts were well-finished, something I find new brands often miss when they’re building new bikes. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</span></figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-XCR-TT-seattube.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Decathalon--XCR-TT-seattube\" width=\"1500\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-XCR-TT-seattube.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Decathalon-XCR-TT-seattube.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>Designed in Flanders. (Photo: Alvin Holbrook/CyclingTips)</span></figcaption></figure>","author":"Alvin Holbrook","siteTitle":"CyclingTips","siteHash":"30feca30fb3902119bf2da6559e7337232527b61c9abe0a00f5d7543c6aa6c84","entryHash":"3595ab66c0d3e1b7096d7dbea37fcc758dfa902db51143d03057405f5165b583","category":"Cycling"}